<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-895-462  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 895 462.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC World  Dec 1989 v7 n12 p71(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsoft/Apple alliance stuns industry; redefining &quot;PostScriptcompatible&quot; for OS/2 fonts. (Industry Outlook)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bender, Eric.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microsoft and Apple Computer Inc agree to share the same fontscaling and printer/page-description technology in OS/2Presentation Manager (PM) and future Macintosh system software.andO;Apple will supply its Royal font technology and Microsoft willprovide the page-description software based on a superset ofAdobe's PostScript.andP;  Third-party font vendors and applicationssuppliers will still be able to offer fonts and alternative fonttechnology.andP;  PM users benefit by having a single imaging modelshowing on screen what the printed output will look like exactlyand by being able to swap documents with Macintosh users withoutlosing fonts.andP;  The deal was a surprise because of the legalbattles between Apple and Microsoft over copyright issues andbecause it is the first time Microsoft has moved away from IBM'sstandard version of PM.andP;  The effect of the deal on PostScript andAdobe is discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (contracts)Apple Computer Inc. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    MSFT; AAPL.andO;Product:   OS/2 Presentation Manager (Graphical user interface) (design andconstruction).andO;Topic:     FontsDesktop PublishingPage Description LanguagesCooperative AgreementSoftware PublishersOperating Environments.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   John Warnock. (portrait)Bill Gates. (portrait)John Sculley. (portrait)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>